    rationale: "In the context of chronic liver disease with stigmata (spider angiomas, palmar erythema), a hand tremor is most likely asterixis \u2014 a flapping tremor caused by hepatic encephalopathy. The failing liver cannot adequately convert ammonia to urea, leading to hyperammonemia. Ammonia crosses the blood-brain barrier and impairs astrocyte function, causing the characteristic metabolic flap. Wernicke's encephalopathy (thiamine deficiency) is possible in alcoholics but presents with the classic triad of confusion, ophthalmoplegia, and ataxia. Essential tremor is a diagnosis of exclusion. Peripheral neuropathy causes sensory loss and weakness, not a flapping tremor.",
