    rationale: "The combination of methylene blue (MAO-A inhibitor) and sertraline (SSRI) carries a significant risk of serotonin syndrome. The appropriate response is multidisciplinary: discuss the risk with the surgeon (who may be able to use alternative mapping agents such as isosulfan blue or technetium-99m colloid, which do not inhibit MAO-A), and consult with the prescribing physician about the feasibility of temporarily holding sertraline. Simply proceeding and monitoring is inadequate \u2014 serotonin syndrome can be severe and life-threatening. Cyproheptadine is a treatment for serotonin syndrome, not a prophylactic agent. Abruptly discontinuing sertraline on the morning of surgery is inappropriate \u2014 SSRIs require gradual tapering and the decision requires prescriber involvement.",
