    rationale: "Spider angiomas (dilated arterioles with radiating vessels), scleral icterus (bilirubin deposition indicating hyperbilirubinemia), and palmar erythema (peripheral vasodilation from estrogen accumulation due to impaired hepatic metabolism) are classic stigmata of chronic liver disease and hepatic synthetic failure. Their presence indicates the liver is failing to synthesize clotting factors, warranting coagulation studies (PT/INR). Bilateral lower extremity pitting edema can occur in liver disease (from hypoalbuminemia and portal hypertension) but is nonspecific and seen in many conditions (heart failure, venous insufficiency). Conjunctival injection is nonspecific and not a stigma of liver disease.",
