    rationale: "Proximal (iliofemoral) DVT carries approximately a 50% risk of pulmonary embolism if untreated, due to the large thrombus burden and proximity to the inferior vena cava. Calf (distal) DVT carries a lower but non-negligible PE risk \u2014 estimated at 1\u20135% for isolated calf DVT, with higher risk if the thrombus propagates proximally (which occurs in approximately 20\u201330% of untreated cases). The clinical implication is that calf DVT should not be dismissed as benign, particularly in high-risk surgical patients. Calf thrombi are not more mobile than proximal thrombi; the higher PE risk with proximal DVT reflects greater thrombus volume.",
