    rationale: "The Homan sign \u2014 calf pain elicited by forced dorsiflexion of the foot \u2014 has poor sensitivity (approximately 50%) and poor specificity for DVT. False positives occur with muscle strain, Achilles tendinitis, and other musculoskeletal conditions. False negatives are common because many DVT patients do not experience pain with dorsiflexion. Additionally, forced dorsiflexion in a patient with DVT carries a theoretical risk of dislodging the thrombus. For these reasons, clinical guidelines recommend against using the Homan sign as a diagnostic maneuver, favoring validated scoring systems (Wells score) combined with D-dimer and compression ultrasound. The test does not require special equipment; its abandonment is based on poor diagnostic performance.",
